metadata.title: ScienceDirect ScienceDirect Study about the Effect of Addition of Carbon Nanofibers on the Strain-Rate Sensitivity of Thermoplastic Polymer Matrix Nanocomposites Manufactured by Ultrasonic Processing

abstract.text: Polymer nanocomposites based on polypropylene (PP) reinforced with carbon nanofibers (CNFs) at a fixed concentration of 0.5% w/w were prepared by precipitation from liquid solutions of PP and CNFs. Ultrasonic processing was used as the primary process for mixing both PP and CNFs in the the solvent, while mechanical stirring was also used as a control process to prepare similar samples. Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) shows that the ultrasonic processing influences little on the thermal stability of the polymer material. Moreover, ultrasonically-processed PP shows higher tensile strength and better ductility, compared to those of the neat PP. Although the mechanically-processed PP has about 10% higher tensile strength than the ultrasonically-processed one, it is observed that there is a significant deterioration in its ductility due to the dissolution of calcium carbonate which is used as an additive for the neat PP. The advantage of significantly reduced material processing time, increased mixing efficiency, and increase in thermal stability and mechanical properties of ultrasonically-processed PPs indicated that the ultrasonic processing is relatively more effective and efficient mixing process compared to mechanical stirring for preparation of the polymer and its nanocomposite. Tensile tests were also conducted using quasi-static strain rates from 10 -4 to 10 -1 s -1 in order to obtain the tensile strength, elongation at fracture, and the elastic modulus of injection molded polymer and its nanocomposite. PP-CNF nanocomposites exhibited higher strain-rate sensitivity within the tested strain range, compared to the neat PP. Both the neat PP and PP-CNF nanocomposite exhibited strain-rate dependent material properties, showing an increase in tensile strength, and decrease in elongation with increasing strain rates.

body_text.text: The viscoelastic nature of the deformation behavior of many polymer materials is derived from the inherent characteristics of polymer chains. The varying lengths of polymer molecules, their tendency to organize in different conformations, and mutual interactions among these molecules are some of the key contributing factors responsible for the unique mechanical response of polymer materials under different loading conditions. The mechanical response of viscoelastic materials subjected to different loading conditions is exhibited in the form of strain-rate sensitivity, stress-relaxation, and creep. In particular, the strain-rate sensitivity of the mechanical properties of thermoplastic polymers is an important consideration for material selection in engineering applications related to load bearing and impact resistance capabilities. body_text.section: Introduction

body_text.text: The viscoelastic nature of the deformation behavior of many polymer materials is derived from the inherent characteristics of polymer chains. The varying lengths of polymer molecules, their tendency to organize in different conformations, and mutual interactions among these molecules are some of the key contributing factors responsible for the unique mechanical response of polymer materials under different loading conditions. The mechanical response of viscoelastic materials subjected to different loading conditions is exhibited in the form of strain-rate sensitivity, stress-relaxation, and creep. In particular, the strain-rate sensitivity of the mechanical properties of thermoplastic polymers is an important consideration for material selection in engineering applications related to load bearing and impact resistance capabilities. Deformation at slow strain rates of a viscoelastic material is analogous to that of viscous fluid, showing a proportional response between stress and strain. At fast strain rates, the deformation behavior is similar to that of a stiff or elastic 48th SME North American Manufacturing Research Conference, NAMRC 48 (Cancelled due to material. However, these extreme modes of deformation at different strain rates are idealized cases, and polymers typically exhibit a combination of both modes of deformation at a given strain rate [1] . Different mechanical models have been used to explain the viscoelastic behavior of polymers on the basis of Hooke's law, using combinations of elastic springs and dashpots. Two of the simplest models that use these concepts are the Maxwell model and Kelvin/Voight model. The Maxwell model attempts to explain viscoelasticity using a spring and dashpot connected in series, but this model can only express stress relaxation. On the other hand, the Voight model explains viscoelasticity in terms of a spring and dashpot connected in parallel, but this model can only express the creep behavior. The standard linear model is useful for explaining both stress relaxation and creep in a single model. It combines a spring in parallel with a Maxwell element. During stress relaxation, the isolated spring maintains original strain, whereas the Maxwell element is responsible for stress relaxation. During creep, there is an instantaneous response from the two springs as they are in parallel and can extend immediately. Although this model provides a decent approximation of the viscoelastic behavior of polymers, in practice, real polymers have various different stress relaxation mechanisms which require a lot of different elements for effective explanation of the behavior. One of the examples of models to explain the complicated behavior can be using multiple Maxwell elements in parallel, each of which have their own relaxation times, and the stress is equivalent to the sum of stresses in individual element [1] [2] [3] [4] . Recent models such as the elastic-viscoelastic-viscoplastic model [5] , and the Hyperelasto-Visco-Hysteresis (HVH) [6] [7] [8] take into consideration the influence of polymer chain conformations on the stress relaxation behavior at different strain rates. The stress relaxation is affected by a change in the proportions of various orientational and conformational states of the polymer molecules under applied stress [1, 4] . Such constitutive models of viscoelastic materials have been applied to predict the deformation behavior of polymer materials supported by experimental data from mechanical property tests of thermoplastic polymers. However, with the advent of polymer matrix composite materials composed of a wide variety of reinforcements and difference in manufacturing processes, there is now a need for a systematic study of strain-rate sensitivity of mechanical properties of such materials to gain insight into their viscoelastic behavior.
body_text.section: Introduction

body_text.text: The need for high performance thermoplastic polymers for use in more demanding engineering applications has led to the development of polymer matrix composite materials containing micro-and nanoscale reinforcements. In particular, polymer nanocomposite materials are attractive for such cases due to the enhancement of mechanical properties with a lower volume fraction of nanomaterials compared to larger scale reinforcements [9] [10] [11] . Additionally, the presence of reinforcements in the polymer matrix also modifies the viscoelastic properties of the polymer nanocomposite. The method of incorporation of nanomaterials into the polymer matrix and the resulting effect on the polymer chain structure will also affect the viscoelastic properties of the polymer. Mechanical stirring and ultrasonic processing of polymer solutions are two widely used approaches used to incorporate nanomaterials in liquid state processing of polymer matrix nanocomposites. The physical mechanisms involved in the mixing process can introduce changes in the molecular structure of the polymer chains [12] [13] [14] [15] . Additionally, the degree of dispersion and distribution of nanomaterials in the polymer matrix can also influence the mechanical behavior of the polymer under different loading conditions [16] [17] [18] .
body_text.section: Introduction

body_text.text: The objectives of this research are to study the strain-rate sensitivity of a thermoplastic polymer and understand the effects of processing method and nanomaterial addition to the polymer matrix on the strain-rate sensitivity of the polymer. Polypropylene (PP) was used as the thermoplastic material, and carbon nanofibers (CNFs) were used as reinforcements to fabricate PP-CNF nanocomposites. CNFs were added to the PP matrix at a fixed volume fraction of 0.5% w/w using two different approaches such as ultrasonic processing and mechanical stirring of liquid PP solutions. The effect of the processing method and addition of CNFs on the mechanical behavior of the polymer at different strain rates was investigated. The effects of these aspects on the thermal behavior of the polymer was also investigated.
body_text.section: Introduction

body_text.text: For preparation of PP-CNF nanocomposites, carbon nanofibers or CNFs (Hanwha Chemical, South Korea) were mixed with PP pellets (LNS Technologies, USA) dissolved in o-xylene (Alfa Aesar, USA). The CNFs had a diameter of 150 nm and length of 6 μm. Both CNFs and PP pellets were mixed in the solvent using two different mixing methods such as ultrasonic processing and mechanical stirring.
body_text.section: Experimental

body_text.text: Ultrasonic processing of CNFs in PP solution was performed in an ultrasonic processing cell. The geometric configuration of the ultrasonic processing cell was selected based on a computational model which predicted the best performance for acoustic cavitation and acoustic streaming. The geometrical configuration includes the depth of immersion of the ultrasonic probe, volume of liquid, and the size and shape of the ultrasonic processing cell. Details of the geometrical configuration selection are reported in our earlier works [19, 20] . The ultrasonic processing cell was constructed from a borosilicate glass tube with one end closed with a glass plate. The glass plate was sealed with a heat-resistant silicone-based adhesive. The ultrasonic processing cell was first filled with oxylene solvent, which was then heated to a temperature of 100°C on a hotplate. PP pellets were then introduced into the preheated solvent at a ratio of 1:10, and an ultrasonic probe (QSonica Q700, USA) was immersed into the ultrasonic processing cell. CNFs were then gradually introduced into the PP-xylene mixture at a concentration of 0.5% w/w, while the ultrasonic probe is active. The amplitude of the tip of the ultrasonic probe was maintained at 60 μm for a period of 30 minutes. The temperature of the mixture of PP and CNFs in oxylene was kept constant at 100°C throughout the ultrasonic processing step. Although ultrasonic processing is effective for mixing CNFs in the hot liquid PP solution, the state of dispersion and distribution of CNFs in the final PP-CNF sol nanocomposite solution can be changed upon its cooling and solidification. To mitigate this issue, the hot PP-CNF nanocomposite solution was quenched in a bath of cold water immediately after ultrasonic processing was completed. The remaining solvent and water was evaporated by prolonged heating at 100°C in a fume hood for a duration of 48 hours, after which a dry mass of solid PP-CNF nanocomposite was obtained. Neat PP was also prepared without the addition of CNFs using the same conditions described for ultrasonic processing. The solidified materials were cut into smaller pieces for use in subsequent injection molding.
body_text.section: Preparation of PP-CNF nanocomposites using ultrasonic processing

body_text.text: Separate PP-CNF nanocomposites were prepared by mixing CNFs into a heated mixture of PP pellets in o-xylene. For dissolution of PP pellets in o-xylene, the solvent was first preheated to a temperature of 140°C. This temperature is close to the boiling point of o-xylene. PP pellets were added to the hot o-xylene at a ratio of 1:10. CNFs were then added to the mixture of PP and o-xylene at a concentration of 0.5% w/w. The mixture of PP and CNFs in hot o-xylene was prepared in a flat-bottomed conical flask which placed on a hotplate with a magnetic stirrer. The conical flask was immersed in a bath of heated mineral oil to maintain uniform heating of the contents of the flask. Stirring of the entire mixture was accomplished by a magnetic stir bar placed inside the flask. In order to avoid evaporation of the solvent during the stirring process, a reflux condenser was attached to the conical flask. The mixture was stirred at a speed of 850 RPM for a duration of 2 hours. After completion of stirring, the hot PP-CNF solution was quenched and dried in the process as described previously. Similar conditions were also used to prepare neat PP without addition of CNFs using mechanical stirring.
body_text.section: Preparation of PP-CNF nanocomposites using mechanical stirring

body_text.text: Tensile test specimens were fabricated by injection molding of both neat PP and PP-CNF nanocomposites into a two-part multi-cavity mold. The mold produced four individual dumbbell shaped flat specimens in a single run. The geometry of each of these specimens conformed with the Type V dimensions specified in the standard ASTM D638-14 [21] , as shown in Fig. 1 . Plastic injection into the mold was accomplished using a manually operated desktop injection molding machine (Model 150A, LNS Technologies, USA). Tensile test specimens for four different processing methods were prepared, which are listed in Table 1 . Mechanical properties of all specimens were obtained using quasi-static tensile tests performed on a universal testing machine (Instron Model 1125, Instron, USA) In order to study strain-rate dependent tensile behavior of the both neat PP and PP-CNF nanocomposites, the tensile tests were performed with strain rates ranging from 10 -4 to 10 -1 s -1 . For each strain rate, tensile tests were conducted using a minimum of four specimens, and one typical curve for each case was used in this study.
body_text.section: Fabrication of tensile test specimens

body_text.text: The thermal behavior of each type of specimens listed in Table 1 was characterized using thermogravimetric analysis (TGA). These tests were performed using a Q5000 IR (TA instruments, USA) TGA instrument. For the TGA tests, samples weighing between 5-15 mg were heated from 25°C to 550°C at a constant heating rate of 10°C/min. The samples were heated in a nitrogen atmosphere with a gas flow rate of 50 cc/min. Temperature dependent weight loss curves obtained from the TGA tests were used to determine the initial degradation temperature, the degradation onset temperature, and the maximum degradation temperature of each sample. These parameters were used to study the effect of the processing method and the addition of CNFs on the thermal stability of the polymer.
body_text.section: Characterization of thermal behavior and chemical structure

body_text.text: Chemical composition of the original neat PP pellets was determined using Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR). FTIR analysis was conducted using a Nicolet Magna-IR spectrometer (Thermo Fisher, USA) within a wavenumber range of 4000 to 525 cm -1 at a resolution of 4 cm -1 over 16 scans.
body_text.section: Characterization of thermal behavior and chemical structure

body_text.text: Before studying the strain-rate sensitivity of the deformation behavior of the neat PP and PP-CNF nanocomposites, the effect of the processing method and the effect of addition of CNFs on the deformation behavior and thermal stability of the different categories of the materials were separately studied.
body_text.section: Results and discussion

body_text.text: Analysis of the effect of the processing method on the deformation behavior of the material was conducted based on the tensile test results obtained at a fixed quasi-static strain rate of 10 -2 s -1 . Typical stress-strain curves obtained for the neat PP specimens are shown in Fig. 2 . The corresponding average with standard deviation of tensile strength and elongation values are listed in Table 2 . The tensile strength of the neat PP polymer subjected to either of the processing methods showed an increase in their magnitude when compared to the original neat PP polymer. The change in mechanical behavior based on processing method of the original polymer can be attributed to the reorganization of filler materials present in the original polymer. Mineral-based fillers are typically added to commercial PP materials as a reinforcing agent to enhance their tensile strength and toughness. In order to verify the presence and type of filler in the PP matrix, FTIR analysis was conducted on the residue obtained from one of the TGA tests of the neat PP samples. The FTIR spectrum of this residue is shown in Fig.  3 . From this FTIR spectrum, three intense peaks can be observed at wavenumbers of 1795 cm -1 , 1412 cm -1 , and 875 cm -1 , which indicate the presence of the compound calcium carbonate (CaCO3). CaCO3 is typically treated with acrylic acid to enhance the dispersion of the filler in the polymer matrix. The surface treatment of CaCO3 results in the formation of calcium acrylate, which can enhance the bonding between CaCO3 and the PP matrix. During processing of PP in the solvent o-xylene, the calcium acrylate is also dissolved along with PP in the solvent. In case of processing PP by mechanical stirring, it is possible that the dissolution of the calcium acrylate can negatively affect the interfacial bonding between the CaCO3 filler particles and the PP matrix. The dispersion and distribution of these filler particles can be affected by the processing method. In the case of neat PP processed by mechanical stirring, increased agglomeration of the filler can lead to a reduction in the ductility, as can be seen in the stressstrain curve for specimen PP2.
body_text.section: Influence of processing methods on deformation behavior and thermal properties

body_text.text: Compared to the specimen PP2, the decrease in the tensile strength of neat PP processed using ultrasonic processing (specimen PP3) can be attributed to the degradation of the polymer by acoustic cavitation. The energy released during acoustic cavitation occurring in ultrasonic processing of polymers can cause scission of long polymer chains, leading to a reduction in the molecular weight of the polymer [36]. However, the ductility of specimen PP3 is similar to that of the original neat PP (specimen PP1). Compared to case of specimen PP2, this behavior can be attributed to achieving a better dispersion of the mineral fillers using ultrasonic processing. Free radicals formed due to chain scission during ultrasonic processing can act as sites for enhanced attraction toward the CaCO3 filler particles [16, 37] . The enhanced bonding strength between the filler particles and PP matrix, combined with the better dispersion is a potential reason for the retention of ductility in the ultrasonically processed specimens. The effect of polymer chain degradation due to processing of polymer is reflected in the polymer's thermal stability. The results of the TGA tests of all neat PP samples were subsequently analyzed.
body_text.section: Influence of processing methods on deformation behavior and thermal properties

body_text.text: TGA curves of the original neat PP, and the neat PP prepared using mechanical stirring and ultrasonic processing are shown in Fig. 4 . The initial degradation temperature (Tint1) is measured at 1% weight loss of polymer. The onset temperature (Tonset) is defined as the point of interception of the Saheem Absar/ Procedia Manufacturing 00 (2019) 000-000 extension of the predegradation portion with the tangent to the steepest portion of the mass curve during degradation. The maximum temperature of the derivative of the TGA curve (Tmax) is defined at the maximum of the weight loss. The thermal stability of the PP polymer is decreased after being subjected to mechanical stirring and ultrasonic processing. The corresponding characteristic thermal degradation temperatures are listed in Table 3 . Based on the thermal parameters obtained from the TGA curves, it is evident that ultrasonic processing of the polymer solution did not result in a significant change in the thermal stability of the neat PP polymer, compared to that of the neat PP polymer prepared using mechanical stirring. Polymer chain degradation induced by ultrasonic processing of the polymer solution is thus not as significant compared to that induced by mechanical stirring. Compared to the original neat PP polymer, the thermal stability of the polymer is decreased by about 3% when subjected to either of the processing methods.
body_text.section: Influence of processing methods on deformation behavior and thermal properties

body_text.text: The influence of addition of CNFs on the mechanical properties of PP polymer were studied using the tensile tests conducted at a fixed quasi-static strain rate of 10 -2 s -1 . The corresponding average with standard deviation of tensile strength and elongation values of two different specimens prepared by ultrasonic processing, PP3 and PPNC2are listed in Table 4 . No dramatic changes in the mechanical properties of the polymer are evident. This behavior can be attributed to the relatively low volume fraction of CNFs in the PP matrix. However, there is a small increase in ductility in the PP-CNF nanocomposite, compared to the neat PP. This behavior can be attributed to the stronger interactions and improved adhesion in polymer structure. In order to observe whether the addition of CNFs into the PP matrix has an effect on the thermal stability of the polymer, TGA tests were conducted on these categories of samples. The corresponding TGA curves are shown in Fig.  5 . From the TGA curves of neat PP and PP-CNF nanocomposites both prepared using ultrasonic processing, a minor decrease in thermal stability is observed. The low volume fraction of CNFs in the PP matrix therefore does not pose a significant effect on the chain degradation of the polymer. Additionally, as shown in Table 5 , when compared to the PP-CNF nanocomposite processed by mechanical stirring, ultrasonically processed PP-CNF showed an increase in the characteristic degradation temperatures, which indicated higher thermal stability. Based on the advantages presented by ultrasonic processing in terms of reduced processing time, higher mixing efficiency, and higher thermal stability, ultrasonic processing can be considered as a feasible method for preparation of PP-CNF nanocomposites. Consequently, the strain-rate sensitivity of the deformation behavior of ultrasonically processed neat PP and PP-CNF were compared with the behavior of the original unprocessed neat PP polymer.
body_text.section: Influence of addition of CNFs on deformation behavior and thermal properties

body_text.text: The strain-rate sensitivity of the deformation behavior of PP and PP-CNF nanocomposites were studied by performing the tensile tests at strain rates from 10 -4 s -1 to 10 -1 s -1 . The comparison of the strain-rate dependent deformation behavior was carried out with the unprocessed neat PP polymer, the ultrasonically processed PP polymer, and the ultrasonically processed PP-CNF nanocomposite. The results are shown in Fig. 6 , and the average and standard deviation of the tensile strength and the elongation at fracture of the different types of PP specimens are listed in Tables 6 and Table 7 , respectively. The original neat PP shows a log-linear relationship between the tensile strength and the strain rate in log-log scale plot, as shown in Fig. 6(a) . The PP-CNF nanocomposites processed through the ultrasonic processing follow the same trend as seen in the neat polymers, but exhibiting a sharp increased tensile strength. The presence of CNFs in the PP matrix can restrict the PP molecular chain mobility and the stress relaxation near fiber ends, which can be a contributing to higher strain-rate sensitivity of the PP-CNF nanocomposites. On the other hand, the elongation at fracture of the neat PP has a log-linear decrease with increasing strain rate, as shown in Fig. 6(b) .
body_text.section: Influence of processing method and addition of CNFs on the strain-rate sensitivity of deformation behavior

body_text.text: With the addition of CNFs in the PP matrix, the negative slope of the strain-rate sensitivity for the elongation at fracture becomes smaller than that of the neat PP, which can be attributed to the pull-out failure of CNFs caused by less stress relaxation near fiber ends and less polymer chain alignment to the loading direction at high strain rates. As the strain rate decreases, polymer chains are prone to the stress relaxation near fiber ends, which induces easiler deformation showing lower tensile strength with higher ductility.
body_text.section: Influence of processing method and addition of CNFs on the strain-rate sensitivity of deformation behavior

body_text.text: The strain-rate dependent deformation behavior of PP and PP-CNF nanocomposites has a strong relationship with the stress relaxation processes occurring in the polymer chains under applied loads. For a semi-crystalline polymer, the process for stress relaxation involves two relaxation processes, one in the crystallites and the other in the amorphous zone [1] . Stress relaxation occurs by chain movement through the crystallites which causes an additional shearing in the amorphous zone. As the yielding behavior of the polymer is dependent on its specific stress relaxation processes, an increase in the strain rate leads to a reduction in the ductility of the polymer. Yielding behavior of the polymer is affected by the ratio of the applied strain rates to the respective relaxation processes of the polymer, and, as this ratio increases, i.e. as the strain increases, the restriction to plastic flow increases in the polymer which leads to a brittleness in the polymer. As the restriction to plastic flow increases with an increase in the strain rate, the stress also increases as a response to this restriction of the plastic flow. As the plastic flow experiences a restriction, the molecules become capable of handling higher loads leading to further increase in stress.
body_text.section: Influence of processing method and addition of CNFs on the strain-rate sensitivity of deformation behavior

body_text.text: In this study, experimental work has been done to study the effect of ultrasonic processing and the addition of CNFs on the mechanical properties, thermal behavior, and the strain-rate sensitivity of the polymer system. PP tensile test specimens have been manufactured through the ultrasonic processing and injection-molded following the standard ASTM D638-14. Compared to the mechanically-stirred PPs, ultrasonicallyprocessed PPs retain their ductility similar to the neat PP, and there is a significant reduction in the preparation time. Their thermal behavior studied using TGA shows that there is only a little change in the degradation temperature, indicating that the ultrasonic processing is relatively more efficient and effective processing method compared to mechanical stirring for preparation of the polymer and its nanocomposite.
body_text.section: Conclusions and future work

body_text.text: Similarly to the neat PP which has shown a strain-rate sensitivity with the tested range from 10 -4 to 10 -1 s -1 , the fabricated nanocomposite with CNFs also shows a similar trend of strain-rate sensitivity, but it shows a sharp increase in the tensile strength. At higher strain rates, CNFs added in the matrix restrict the polymer molecule flowing and stress relaxation near them, inducing more efficiency in load transferring, which results in higher tensile strength, showing lower ductility. , but its ductility is still remained Future investigations related to this work include the study of the effect of variation in the volume fraction of CNFs on the strain-rate sensitivity and thermal stability of the polymer. Additionally, the influence of processing method and addition of nanofibers on crystallinity of the polymer matrix will be studied. Microstructural analysis of the polymer matrix will also be performed to observe the effect of the polymer processing method on the degree of dispersion and dispersion of the CNFs in the polymer matrix. Higher levels of strain rates up to 10 4 s -1 will be performed in order to gain further understanding of the strain-rate sensitivity.
body_text.section: Conclusions and future work
